description: From Middle English misdon, from Old English misdōn (“to do evil, transgress, do amiss, err”), from Proto-Germanic *missadōną (“to do wrongly”), from *missa- (“mis-”), *dōną (“to do”). Corresponding to mis- +‎ do. Cognate with Old Frisian misdūa (“to misdo”), Dutch misdoen (“to offend, do wrongly”), Middle Low German misdōn (“to misdo”), Middle High German missetuon (“to transgress, offend, blame”). More at mis-, do.

verbs.description: misdo (third-person singular simple present misdoes, present participle misdoing, simple past misdid, past participle misdone)

entries.meaning: (archaic, transitive) To do harm to; to injure, mistreat.
